-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, Philippines: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-07-05T22:16:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-05/japan-china-india-malaysia-philippines-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
cabinet meeting in the morning.  
 The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on Japan’s leading and coincident indexes for May. The
coincident index, a composite of 11 indicators including factory
production and retail sales, declined to 101.2 in May from 101.3
in April, according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  
 The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. in
Tokyo the amount of five-year Japanese government bonds it plans
to sell on July 13.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.105 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.76 per dollar at 7:05 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell 28 billion yuan
($4.1 billion) of five-year debt tomorrow and the central bank
will auction 6 billion yuan of 1-year notes.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.62 percent. The yuan was at 6.7758 per dollar.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 35 billion
rupees ($749 million) selling treasury bills at an auction
tomorrow. It will offer 20 billion rupees of 91-day bills and 15
billion rupees of 182-day notes, according to the central bank.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.62
percent. The rupee was at 46.78.  
 Indonesia: The government plans to sell one-year treasury
bills and auction bonds maturing in 10, 15 and 30 years.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
8.26 percent, according to Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,063.  
 Malaysia: The central bank plans to sell 1.5 billion
ringgit ($468 million) of 91-day fixed-income securities and 1
billion ringgit of 61-day Islamic debt tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.50 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.207.  
 Philippines: A government report will show annual inflation
was unchanged at 4.3 percent in June, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg News survey.  
 The government plans to sell 8.5 billion pesos ($183
million) of 20-year debt.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.89 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 46.475.  
 South Korea: The government will report foreign direct
investment for the three months ended June 30. Inflows fell 8.2
percent in the previous quarter from a year earlier, a second
straight decline.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.40 percent. The won was at 1,223.30.  
 Thailand: The central bank will today sell 20 billion baht
($617 million) of 28-day bills, 15 billion baht each of 91- and
182-day notes and 30 billion baht of 364-day securities.  
 The yield on the 5.375 percent bond maturing in December
2019 was 3.24 percent. The baht was at 32.44.  
